##Alive, in Wuhan

Southreviews

Functional presentation, the power of calm

Wuhan has become a place that people pay close attention to every day.

It's not just the cold statistics that matter, it's the temperature and power of the city. The hustle and bustle fades, and the everyday Wuhan takes on a new look.

The streets were once filled with enthusiasm, carrying huge numbers of residents, and the city's past was glorious and bloody, with the imprint of history written in blood and flesh. But now, "being alive" has become a painful daily memory.

The battle around the epidemic, everyone is doing their best. Every day, every moment, Wuhan happened in Dribs and drabs are worth remembering.

The camera was there to see it.

A mother cautiously touches her son's head and takes his temperature

Pedestrians and vehicles pass through the closed south China Seafood Wholesale Market in Wuhan

In the early hours of January 23, Wuhan issued a notice to suspend the city's bus, subway, ferry and long-distance passenger services from 10:00 a.m. on the same day, and to close the airport and railway stations to the Han corridor. That day, citizens went to buy daily necessities

On January 27, the fourth day of the "city closure" , residents of Wuhan continued to exercise

Residents take their dogs out to buy vegetables at a farmers'market on Jan. 31. On the same day, the World Health Organization declared the new coronavirus epidemic as a "public health emergency of international concern"

Hawkers still in business

Some residents wear sunglasses for protection

Dog Walker

There are old people flying kites in the park

An elderly man pulls a trolley as he walks by on Feb. 5

On January 17, medical staff transferred the patient to the Golden Pool Hospital

Security personnel take the temperature of passengers at a pier on Jan. 22

On Jan. 24, excavators were working to build the 1,000-bed Vulcan Mountain Hospital

Workers carry a roadblock as construction continues at Mount Thor Hospital

The Wuhan International Convention and Exhibition Center is under renovation on Feb. 4

A renovated living room in Wuhan. This will be a "bunker hospital" for the sick

A worker cleans construction waste from a living room in Wuhan

They're sterilizing the steps

Couriers are delivering supplies to hospitals, and because of the temporary closure of the city's transportation system, couriers have become an important means of transporting supplies

Messenger on break

Most of them are wearing full protective gear as they move through the city

On February 1st, the delivery guy with the electric car

An empty overpass

A road with almost no pedestrians in sight

Usually, Chuhehan street is one of the most popular pedestrian streets in the city

Once bustling shops lined both sides of the road, they are now all closed. Behind the man on the motorcycle is Yellow Crane Tower

On January 22, the old man photographed passing boats on the banks of the Yangtze River

Pedestrians on the banks of the Yangtze River

The city is still as usual, it may be the Yangtze River sunset
